Agriculture, Land Reform and Rural Development Minister, Thoko Didiza, says that the Inter-Ministerial committee on land reform and agriculture has responded to all recommendations it's received. #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The Presidential Advisory Panel on Land Reform has recommended a review of the Ingonyama Trust Act. This as government still mulls over the issue of of rural land. Minister of Agriculture, Land Reform and Rural Development, Thoko Didiza, addressed the media in Pretoria on Thursday. READ: Land reform can deliver 'social cohesion': report "Their proposal is that there must be a review of the Ingonyama Trust Act or maybe a repeal of that legislation." The Cabinet received 73 recommendations from the panel in July this year. In August, the Congress of Traditional Leaders of South Africa (Contralesa) stated that the Ingonyama Trust cannot be repealed or reviewed without the Zulu king's consent. King Goodwill Zwelithini is the sole trustee of the trust which controls about three million hectares of land in KwaZulu-Natal. AmaZulu King Goodwill Zwelithini has vowed to protect his land. Minister of Agriculture, Land Reform and Rural Development, Thoko Didiza, briefs the media on the recommendations of the Presidential Advisory Panel on Land.